##29-year-old doctor Peng Yinhua died in the line of duty, the wedding photo became a suicide photo

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Pictures of Peng Yinhua are covered with chrysanthemums. China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily Reporter, Wang Xinxin / photo

Wuhan, Feb. 22, China Youth Daily

By Wang Xinxin and Sun Qingling

Editor, Zhang Guo

Dr. Peng Yinhua is gone.

On February 20,2020, at 21:50, he died of a new coronary pneumonia in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. He was only 29 years old.

In a conference room at Jiangxia District's First People's Hospital where he worked, colleagues held chrysanthemums as they said goodbye to the young doctor who died in the line of duty on February 21. Before he had time to use the wedding anniversary photo was projected on the screen, became a suicide photo.

"I ate your wedding candy, but I couldn't attend your wedding, " a colleague wrote in a nearby notebook. "I kept thinking you'd get better, but I didn't think... "

The Green Hornet video

Peng and his wife were to get married on February 1st, the Eighth Day of the first lunar month. He has invited his colleagues in the department to "make a noise" . There are still unsent invitations in the desk drawer. The wedding was just a ceremony. The young couple had already taken out a marriage license, and the baby had been in the mother's womb for six months. Colleagues joked with him that if he didn't have a wedding, it would be three people.

As with anything so rudely interrupted by the epidemic, the wedding had to be called off. On January 21, Peng Yinhua's respiratory and critical care 3 ward was listed as the second batch of in-patient isolation ward for treating "viral pneumonia of unknown origin" . That night, Peng Yinhua's colleague Li Yingpu was on duty. She remembers treating 40 patients one night and returning to work the next day with more than 100 beds nearly full.

"As the outbreak escalated, he volunteered that everyone was busy with work and he wouldn't go to the wedding, " Chen Hao, director of Ward 3 of the division of respiratory and critical care medicine at Jiangxia District First People's Hospital, told reporters.

"The task was very heavy at that time, and people flocked to us. If we didn't bring in as many patients as possible, they would flow into society and cause the spread of the disease, " Chen said, "All our doctors lived and ate in the hospital for a few days. "

Seeing the current situation, some medical staff have some bad premonition, some people call their families directly, said they may be in the hospital for the New Year.

In the ward, Peng Yinhua and colleagues are the same, receive patients, handle hospitalizations, doctor's orders, but also to appease the panic of patients, busy around the clock. At one point he was on duty for 48 hours straight.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A work photo of Peng Yinhua during the outbreak control by Zhao Ying

"The situation was that if one person took a break, it meant others were more tired, " Ms. Li said, adding that enthusiastic people like Ms. Peng were racing ahead. She was under the impression that even when doctors and nurses said, "Yinhua Peng, give me a hand, " he would drop his work to help.

In the early rush, many medical staff were hit by the virus. Since January 23, Peng has developed low-grade fever and cough. His colleagues were on high alert and examined him on January 25. Medical imaging showed viral pneumonia, but "negative for coronavirus nucleic acid" and "no clear signs of infection. ".

The next day, Peng Yinhua was still not feeling well. His colleagues asked him to have another CT scan of his lungs. "I got it this time, " Chen said.

To this day, colleagues can't trace back to when or where Peng was infected by the virus. Zhao Ying, head nurse in the respiratory and critical care unit, said there were too many suspected patients at the time to know where the infection had come from.

On the night of January 30, Peng Yinhua was transferred to the intensive care unit of Jinyintan hospital because his condition was not under control and was gradually getting worse.

But the disease is still repeated, and sometimes comes news of a stable condition. On February 2, Peng ate two bowls of green vegetables and lean meat congee for breakfast, she remembers. "We think it's a good thing that he's getting better and everyone is encouraging him. "

By February 9, Peng's condition had worsened, and Oxygenation had declined. On February 10, Li heard that he had been intubated.

Zhao Ying was also concerned about his young colleague. Once she asked Peng if she wanted to drink milk and got a reply: "If it's convenient, bring me some. " This made her feel better. Peng Yinhua also told colleagues on Wechat, I must insist, I still have not born children.

His pregnant wife was cheering him on. "remember that I will always be there for you, love you, and the baby, and we will wait for you to come back, " his wife told him in a screenshot of the chat on Wechat, the paper reported

"thanks to my wife's concern, I will definitely try harder and go home early, " said Peng, who is going through difficult therapy in the Feb. 8 conversation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph by Zhao Ying, my shot

In order to treat Peng Yinhua, the hospital had considered using plasma therapy to inject him with the plasma donated by the convalescent patient with NCP, but the first batch of plasma could not be matched. A 200-milliliter convalescent plasma match was found on February 12, but he continued to deteriorate after receiving the injection.

On the night of February 20, Peng Yinhua died after being resuscitated.

A Weibo account first broke the news of Peng's death. At one point, Li Yingpu didn't believe it was true. "It was too much for anyone. We knew that someone would die, but we never thought it would be a friend. We never thought it would go so fast. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A message from a colleague. Wang Xinxin / photo by Zhongqing net reporter, Zhongqing daily

That night, some stayed up all night, others posted messages of condolence to him on Facebook, and others replaced their heads with lighted candles. In the Department of respiratory and critical care medicine at the First People's Hospital in Jiangxia, colleagues on duty could hardly find a full moment of silence for him as the Split Second continued its work on patients.

"We're scared, too, but we're not going back, " Zhao Ying said, "people say, 'I'm not afraid, ' and I say, are you really not afraid? Are you a saint? It's not that you're not afraid, it's that when you get into that environment and see the patient, we forget to be afraid. "
